      "source": [
        "# Trump 2026 News Log Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "This notebook parses and analyzes the `trump2026.md` file, which tracks key developments in the Trump administration during 2026. \n",
        "\n",
        "### Features:\n",
        "1. **Parsing**: Converts unstructured Markdown into a structured Pandas DataFrame.\n",
        "2. **Sentiment Analysis**: Tracks the tone of updates over time.\n",
        "3. **Topic Modeling**: Identifies key themes (e.g., Iran, China, Trade).\n",
        "4. **Visualization**: Generates timelines and sentiment trends.\n",
        "5. **R Integration**: Uses R libraries for high-quality data visualization."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# Install necessary libraries if not present\n",
        "!pip install pandas matplotlib textblob rpy2 seaborn"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import re\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "from textblob import TextBlob\n",
        "import seaborn as sns\n",
        "from datetime import datetime\n",
        "\n",
        "def parse_trump_news(file_path):\n",
        "    with open(file_path, 'r') as f:\n",
        "        content = f.read()\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # Split by updates\n",
        "    updates = re.split(r'## (.*? Update)', content)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    data = []\n",
        "    for i in range(1, len(updates), 2):\n",
        "        header = updates[i]\n",
        "        body = updates[i+1]\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Extract date\n",
        "        date_match = re.search(r'([A-Za-z]+ \\d+, \\d{4})', header)\n",
        "        date_str = date_match.group(1) if date_match else \"Unknown\"\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Extract bullet points (Key Developments)\n",
        "        developments = re.findall(r'\\* \\s*\\*\\*(.*?):\\*\\*(.*)', body)\n",
        "        \n",
        "        for topic, description in developments:\n",
        "            data.append({\n",
        "                'Date': date_str,\n",
        "                'Topic': topic.strip(),\n",
        "                'Description': description.strip(),\n",
        "                'Raw_Date': datetime.strptime(date_str, '%B %d, %Y') if date_str != \"Unknown\" else None\n",
        "            })\n",
        "            \n",
        "    return pd.DataFrame(data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Parse the file\n",
        "df = parse_trump_news('trump2026.md')\n",
        "df.sort_values('Raw_Date', inplace=True)\n",
        "df.head()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Sentiment Analysis\n",
        "We'll use `TextBlob` to calculate the polarity of each development."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "def get_sentiment(text):\n",
        "    return TextBlob(text).sentiment.polarity\n",
        "\n",
        "df['Sentiment'] = df['Description'].apply(get_sentiment)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Average sentiment by date\n",
        "sentiment_trend = df.groupby('Date')['Sentiment'].mean().reset_index()\n",
        "sentiment_trend['Raw_Date'] = pd.to_datetime(sentiment_trend['Date'])\n",
        "sentiment_trend.sort_values('Raw_Date', inplace=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))\n",
        "plt.plot(sentiment_trend['Date'], sentiment_trend['Sentiment'], marker='o', linestyle='-', color='b')\n",
        "plt.title('Sentiment Trend of Trump 2026 News')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Date')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Average Polarity (-1 to 1)')\n",
        "plt.xticks(rotation=45)\n",
        "plt.grid(True)\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Topic Analysis\n",
        "Which topics are mentioned most frequently?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "topic_counts = df['Topic'].value_counts().head(10)\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
        "sns.barplot(x=topic_counts.values, y=topic_counts.index, palette='viridis')\n",
        "plt.title('Top 10 Mentioned Topics in 2026')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## R Integration with ggplot2\n",
        "Sometimes R's `ggplot2` is superior for specific visualizations. Here is how you can use it within this notebook."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "import rpy2.robjects as robjects\n",
        "from rpy2.robjects import pandas2ri\n",
        "from rpy2.robjects.packages import importr\n",
        "\n",
        "pandas2ri.activate()\n",
        "base = importr('base')\n",
        "ggplot2 = importr('ggplot2')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Convert Pandas DF to R Data Frame\n",
        "r_df = pandas2ri.py2rpy(df)\n",
        "\n",
        "robjects.globalenv['r_df'] = r_df\n",
        "\n",
        "robjects.r('''\n",
        "library(ggplot2)\n",
        "p <- ggplot(r_df, aes(x=Raw_Date, y=Sentiment, color=Topic)) +\n",
        "     geom_point(size=3) +\n",
        "     geom_smooth(aes(group=1), method=\"lm\", se=FALSE, color=\"black\", linetype=\"dashed\") +\n",
        "     theme_minimal() +\n",
        "     labs(title=\"Sentiment Analysis by Topic (R ggplot2)\",\n",
        "          x=\"Date\", y=\"Sentiment Polarity\")\n",
        "print(p)\n",
        "''')"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Search Utility\n",
        "Easily find developments related to specific keywords."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "def search_news(keyword):\n",
        "    return df[df['Description'].str.contains(keyword, case=False) | df['Topic'].str.contains(keyword, case=False)]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example search\n",
        "search_news('Iran')"
      ]
    }
